# Map SITL chirp outputs to flight-test `actuator_outputs_2`

## Context

The chirp SITL runner works, but the user analyzes flight-test logs via **`actuator_outputs_2`**,
which never appears in SITL (SITL has only `actuator_outputs_0`). Goal: reconcile the two so the
chirp can be inspected in SITL the same way as in flight. Chosen approach: **map & compare** (no
flight-code changes), aligning **by output function** rather than by instance index.

### Why the instances differ (root cause — traced in code)
- `actuator_outputs` multi-instance = **one per output *driver*** (`MixingOutput`), assigned in
  advertise/startup order (`platforms/common/uORB/PublicationMulti.hpp:72`,
  `src/lib/mixer_module/mixer_module.cpp:689`). Not a logging setting.
- **SITL = one driver, `pwm_out_sim`, a singleton** (`PWMSim::task_spawn`, can't start twice) ⇒ only
  `actuator_outputs_0` (PWM-µs; servos `output[0–7]`, motors `output[8–9]`) + normalized
  `actuator_outputs_sim` for gazebo.
- **Flight = several drivers**, each its own instance; on this airframe the motors live in board
  defaults (not the shared airframe), on a separate ESC bus.
- The chirp is **instance-independent**: `control_allocator` publishes single-instance
  **`actuator_motors`** (Motor1–12) and **`actuator_servos`** (Servo1–8) before any per-bus mapping;
  every `actuator_outputs_N[ch]` is one of those re-mapped/scaled for one bus via `<PREFIX>_FUNCn`.

### Flight-log finding — VALIDATED on `OD1A064_rpyChirp.ulg`
Ran the correlation mapper (read-only, host pyulog) on the provided flight log:
- Instances present: **`1` and `2`** (no `_0`), both ~94 Hz.
- **`actuator_outputs_2` = `UAVCAN_SV` (servo controller) = the 8 swashplate/elevon servos.** Its
  channels match **Servo1–8 at corr 0.96–0.99**, in `UAVCAN_SV_FUNC1–8` order = `{201,202,203,207,204,205,206,208}`.
- `actuator_outputs_1` = `UAVCAN_EC` = the **2 motors** (`UAVCAN_EC_FUNC1/2 = 101/102`).
- `CA_CHIRP_*` params are **empty** in this log ⇒ the flight roll/pitch/yaw chirp used a *different*
  mechanism than the new `CA_CHIRP` feature → compare by **function + signal shape/frequency**, not
  identical injection.

### The mapping (what the user needs)
| function | flight log | SITL log |
|----------|-----------|----------|
| Servo1–8 (swash 201–206, elevons 207–208) | `actuator_outputs_2[ch]` (UAVCAN_SV order) **and** `actuator_servos[0–7]` | `actuator_outputs_0[0–7]` (PWM_MAIN order) **and** `actuator_servos[0–7]` |
| Motor1–2 (101/102) | `actuator_outputs_1[0–1]` (UAVCAN_EC) **and** `actuator_motors[0–1]` | `actuator_outputs_0[8–9]` **and** `actuator_motors[0–1]` |

`actuator_servos`/`actuator_motors` are **function-indexed and present in both logs** → the canonical,
instance-independent comparison layer. The per-bus `actuator_outputs_N` channel order differs (UAVCAN_SV
vs PWM_MAIN), so aligning raw `actuator_outputs` requires the function map (which the tool builds).

## What gets built — under `Tools/chirp_sysid/` (host-side analysis: pyulog/numpy on the host; the
flight log is not under the container mount, so this runs on the host, not in the container)

### 1. `output_map.py` — function-aware mapper / comparator
- **`--ulog FILE`**: for each `actuator_outputs` instance+channel, identify the carried function by
  correlating the (normalized) channel against every `actuator_motors`/`actuator_servos` channel;
  print `instance:channel → Motor_n/Servo_n (corr)`. Also dump nonzero `*_FUNC*` params as
  cross-check, and flag the chirped axis. (Validated: this produced corr 0.96–0.99 on the flight log.)
- **`--compare SITL.ulg FLIGHT.ulg [--function Servo3|Motor1|…]`**: align by function via the common
  `actuator_servos`/`actuator_motors` layer; report correlation + normalized RMS over the chirp
  window and optionally write an overlay PNG, so the user sees the SITL chirp vs the flight chirp for
  the same physical actuator.

Reuse the ulog pattern already used in runner verification (`pyulog.ULog(path, message_name_filter_list=[…])`, `.data_list`, `.initial_parameters`).

### 2. `OUTPUTS.md` (linked from `README.md`)
The root-cause + the concrete flight finding above (incl. the mapping table and that
`actuator_outputs_2 = UAVCAN_SV servos`), the SITL channel layout, and how to run `output_map.py`.

